notes_fields.Macroscopic_Features: Fruiting body orbicular or linear, confluent, whitish grayish in color, with hyphal pegs visible at low magnifications. Horizontal cracks were numerous and evident in the thickest sporocarps.
notes_fields.Microscopic_Features: Features very difficult to discern because of the presence of crystals and/or resinous matter that obscured everything and did not dissolve in 5% or 10% KOH. Spores were broadly ellipsoid to ellipsoid, length (7.8) 8.2-9.5 (9.8) x width (5.4) 5.8-7.0 (7.2) µm, Q (1.3) 1.3-1.5 (1.5), n=7. A few dendrohyphidia were observed.

results.notes:

results.notes:
Hi, I am a Highschool Student in Virginia who was referred here by the Mycological Association of Washington. I did a science experiment involving Mycorrhizae and was wondering if these images contained any.

There are two principal types I find.
1) Many dark flecks (circled in green)
2) Long dark square shapes within the cells (circled in red)

These roots are mung bean roots which have been cleared of dirt with KOH in an autoclave, and then stained in an autoclave with ink. I did my experiment according to this website (https://mycorrhizas.info/method.html).

These specimen were taken studied at 40x magnification. Additional pictures are available should they be required.

I did some research and have a hunch that the first variant is Ectomycorrhiza whilst the second variant is Arbuscular. But I am no expert so I cannot be sure.

If you have experience with a microscope I would love to hear from you as to whether or not these shapes are fungi.
